              %h5 Op-Ed Article

            %p.large-6.column  
              The great pessimist, Thomas Hobbes based his entire life to the greater understanding of the war and turmoil that mankind has made for itself. Hobbes is famous for his firm concept that men are born greedy, or selfish. Stating that all humans would stoop to certain levels of evil in order to place them in a favorable position above others.
              As a English philosopher, he explored the idea of social contact, or the authority that state has over an individual. He was fascinated by how people allow themselves to become controlled or ruled by a central government. However, Hobbes theories seem contradicting at a certain point.  On one hand Hobbes believes that because of the harsh intention of human nature, people should have a firm central government, like a king that will make all 

           
            %p.large-6.column  
              decisions for the population.  He disliked the base of a Democracy, seeing that the general public couldn’t be trusted to make the right and moral decisions that a government has control over. On the other hand we still have to make an effort to see that the one in charge is stable to lead without moral weakness.  This is where Hobbes direction seems unclear, he is confident in the overwhelming evil of mankind yet he believes in the sanction of a single ruler.
            .byline.large-6.text-right.column - By Kendall Cuthie
            
          
          
